Villages of Islamabad,
Pakistan
Shah Allah Ditta ( هﺎﺷﷲہﺗد ) is a deprived
Pakistani village near Islamabad. It is famous
for the 2000 years old beautiful Buddhist
caves nearby.
The villagers have not yet had the chance to
beneﬁt from this exceptional heritage and
live in indescribable poverty.
Burma Town- Other villages in the region, such as Burma
Town, are in equally diﬃcult situations and are unable to
break the circle of poverty on their own. Until recently,
the children had no access to school and the public
service is totally non-existent.
But together we can change this!
My story
My story is that of a young Swiss woman who is aware of how
lucky she is to have been born by chance in one of the few
places on Earth where life is so easy. Accepting this privilege
without abusing it is one thing, sharing it is another, much
more diﬃcult. How can we allow as many people as possible
to lead a life as beautiful and easy as ours without imposing
our values and respecting their differences? Next autumn, it is
with this objective in mind that I will start a Master's degree in
International Development at the IHEID in Geneva. In the
meantime, I will take advantage of the university summer holidays to start helping those who
need me.
Why Shah Allah Ditta?
While on an academic exchange in Beijing,
China, in 2019, I developed a strong friendship
with Dan, a student in London of Pakistani
origin. His family is committed to improving the
lives of Pakistanis. When I asked him last March
if he knew of any project that could use my
support, it took him no more than an hour to put
me in touch with several local NGOs. So many of
them need
support! Unfortunately we cannot do everything. After a
long reﬂection, I decided to get involved in the projects in
Shah Allah Ditta and Burma Town in collaboration with the
NGOs Akho and Sunbeams.
Partnership with Sunbeams et AKHO
The misery of Shah Allah Ditta and Burma Town has not left the charities Sunbeams and
AKHO indifferent. Both were founded by selﬂess Pakistani women and focus on different
aspects of poverty. With me as an intermediary they are joining forces for eﬃcient projects.
SUNBEAMS
Since 2014 Sunbeams and its founder
Ainee Nasir have opened several schools
in Pakistan to provide affordable quality
education to local children. As a result of
this commitment, more than 3000 children
have seen their future prospects broaden.
In the future they will be able to break the
cycle of poverty in which the community is
currently trapped. Sunbeams is also
involved in other projects to support poor
communities.
https://sunbeams.pk/
AKHO
AKHO, founded by Huma Beg, focuses on
the distribution of food for the poorest and
the empowerment of women. In addition
to food rations, it offers vocational training
where participants learn the art of
dressmaking, catering, etc. The women,
thus equipped with manual skills, are
integrated into the workforce and
participate in raising the standard of living
of their families and community.
http://akho.org.pk
My commitment
My involvement in Shah Allah Ditta and Burma will be mainly focused on the coordination
between Sunbeams and Akho and the development of new joint projects. By supporting me,
you will be improving the lives of dozens of families, empowering hundreds of women and
protecting the cultural heritage of an entire region.
Coordination
Improving coordination between local actors will
increase the eﬃciency of their work while reducing
costs. They will be able to allocate more of their
limited resources to projects and less to
administration. The villagers will beneﬁt even more
from our efforts!
Apart from my coordination work, I will also assist
both associations with their projects.
Eco-tourism
Developing a model of sustainable ecological tourism
beneﬁcial for the locals will be the challenge that will
occupy most of my time. Shah Allah Ditta does not
currently have access to the most basic infrastructure such
as waste collection. How do you attract tourists to an area
where the ground is covered in garbage? Another challenge
is to ensure that the villagers are the main beneﬁciaries of
our work. How do we include them in every aspect of the
future of their area? Finding community-based solutions to
these and other problems is crucial to improving the economic situation of the people and
preserving their wonderful environment.
Women empowerment through work
One aspect that needs to be addressed urgently is the inclusion of all in the common effort
for the region. In Pakistan, men have always had the role of bringing the means of
livelihood home. They are therefore the almost
exclusive economic actors of the community.
Women are excluded from the work force and are
therefore ﬁnancially dependent on their husbands.
Not only is half of the working age population not
allowed to work, at the expense of the economy,
but at the individual level the women of the region
have no freedom. Akho's sewing workshop in
Shah Allah Ditta has already proven to be effective
in helping many women to empower themselves and improve their families' income.Many
more women in the region are wishing to participate and receive education. Unfortunately
their demand has not been met yet because of limited resources. Helping Akho replicating
this successful model in Burma Town so that more women have access to it will be my
third task.
How YOU can make a difference
Donate to support me in this project !
Every cent donated will be invested in the best possible way for the well-being of the most
underprivileged people in Shah Allah Ditta and Burma Town. I will take care of all my
personal expenses (transport, accommodation, food,...). Your contribution could, for
example, ﬁnance the creation of a waste collection system in the village, the adaptation of
houses to accommodate tourists, sewing machines, etc. Once I am there I will be able to see
the needs of the community more clearly and invest our resources where people REALLY
need them.
As an indication, a sewing machine costs about CHF 60.-, an instructor's salary CHF 90.-. To
simply furnish a guest room, it costs at least CHF 250.-.
